Typically, ethnopharmacological studies have focused on isolating and testing the antimicrobial effects of single compounds (
 Cowan, 1999; 
 Eloff, 2019). However, reconstituted plant remedies possess a diverse range of ingredients, and it is increasingly being recognized that these combined effects contribute to the effects of the “whole remedy” (
 Cowan, 1999; 
 Khameneh et al., 2019). The remedies reconstituted and tested in this work are complex plant formulations, and as part of the next steps, it would be important to identify and investigate interactions between the biologically active compounds in the formulations. For this, approaches such as mass spectrometry-based metabolomics that are capable of identifying biologically active compounds in plant extracts (
 Caesar et al., 2019a; 
 Caesar et al., 2019b) can be applied.
